        <p class="largeheading">Fildaren's Gambit<br>
          by Fildaren &amp; Vanalin - Erollisi Marr </p>
        <p class="whitetext9"><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren, son of Finarthin, 
          shrugged his cloak tighter over his shoulders as the lingering cold 
          of winter swept over him. He used his warm breath to blow life back 
          into his aching fingers, all the while casting his blue eyed gaze across 
          the tableau before him. Another two orcs had appeared from inside the 
          tunnel to join the first who had stood guard there for the hour that 
          Fildaren had studied him. The young High Elf’s sensitive ears could 
          hear the loud crunch of the orcs’ boots as they stomped their way towards 
          their companion. Crushbone orcs. By the grace of Tunare he hated Crushbone 
          orcs. They were spreading like a plague across the Greater Faydark and 
          the very thought of their presence here brought a bitter taste to his 
          mouth. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">The Crushbone’s hold on the area, like all 
          things, had started small. Fildaren could remember back a few winters 
          when the first reported sightings of orcs had filtered through to Felwithe. 
          A Dwarven merchant by the name of Nib had braved the long road from 
          the Butcherblock Mountains to ply his trade amongst the fair folk. Fildaren 
          recalled the day when the small band of dwarves had arrived at the gates 
          of the city, their leather armour scarred and tattered, their shiny 
          axes clenched in fists of rage as they told of blue demons descending 
          upon their caravan from the hills. A few hours and a few soothing ales 
          later the dreaded truth was known. The children of Rallos Zek had come 
          to the 1es’ ancient forest home. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren had heeded the signs well. He knew 
          that this would not be a single incident. That was not the nature of 
          the orcs. War and carnage were seeded into their every fibre. He knew 
          that where a few led, more would surely follow. It was up to him, and 
          those like him, to lead the charge against the shadow that would come. 
          With this in mind Fildaren chose to align himself with the Magicians 
          Guild. With time and patience his meager skills in the arcane arts had 
          grown and blossomed. With a thought he could summon a loaf of bread 
          or a fireball of pure destructive force. His apprenticeship completed, 
          Fildaren had pledged allegiance to the Crusaders of the Soul. The Crusaders 
          were a sacred society dedicated to promoting peace and justice and to 
          stemming the flow of evil that ravaged Norrath. It was through this 
          guild that the young High Elven mage saw his chance to turn his heartfelt 
          beliefs into action. The creatures of darkness had to be stopped.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren’s premonitions had been realised. 
          Reports of orc attacks had become more and more frequent, travellers 
          found slaughtered, homes burned and looted until the legions of Crushbone 
          were reported at the very steps of Felwithe and Kelethin. Now an unofficial 
          war raged between the minions of Emperor Crushbone and the Elven folk, 
          joined by the many races of Norrath that opposed the spread of the dark 
          enemy. Bands of adventurers roamed the ancient forest seeking out the 
          invaders and striking a blow any way that they knew. With blade, arrow, 
          staff or spell they sought to drive the enemy from their door.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">All these events had lead Fildaren to this 
          moment. Crouched upon the frosty ground of a lonely knoll in the middle 
          of Greater Faydark. Before him stood the entrance to Crushbone. Two 
          huge bonfires blazed away defiantly along either side of the entrance 
          and the huge black and blood crimson standard of the orcs fluttered 
          in the icy breeze. The image before him was like a sharp slap in the 
          face to the young elf. This was his home and he would rather kiss a 
          troll than stand by while the forest was overrun with orcs. An ironic 
          smile curved his lips as the mental imagery hit home. Kissing trolls 
          was not one of his favourite pastimes. The smile soon faded as the deep, 
          guttural voices of the orcs floated to him across the crisp air.. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Hail Emperor Crush&quot; snarled the 
          two newcomers in unison. Fildaren could hear the loud thud as they slammed 
          their fists into their chests in salute. The guard who he had been studying 
          returned the salute and stood to attention, or what Fildaren thought 
          resembled attention. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Glory to the Emperor&quot; growled the 
          guard in response. All three appeared to be centurions. Thick leather 
          armour covered their muscular chest and shoulders. Their metal helmets 
          were dented and tarnished and they each cradled a rusty short spear 
          in their thick arms. Light cast from the bonfires caused shadows to 
          form and shift across their dark blue skin and their beady red eyes 
          shined with a predatorial fervor. Black lips curled over thick fangs 
          as they struggled to mouth their words.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;We have been sent to help guard. Scouts 
          report elves nearby. Probably smelt foul elf stink.&quot; They each 
          emitted a rumbling snarl which Fildaren could only guess as being laughter.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Need no help guarding. Elves are cowards. 
          Cringing dogs.&quot; This brought another rumble of appreciation from 
          the trio as they assumed their posts along the entrance.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren clenched his jaw involuntarily. &quot;We 
          shall see who the cringing dogs are&quot; he mumbled ominously to himself. 
          The waiting was over. He had been studying the entrance to learn of 
          the movement of the guards but he had missed his chance to strike the 
          solitary guard. He scrubbed his fingers through his snow white hair 
          in annoyance and cursed his procrastination. He had to move before more 
          reinforcements came. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">As silently as he could he backed himself 
          down the small incline until he was shielded from view. He drew himself 
          up to his full height, his deep purple magician’s robe flowing majestically 
          about him, and prepared to draw upon his power. He closed his eyes in 
          concentration. He could feel his mana, his magical essence, flowing 
          through him. It was the pool from which he drew his power and he sensed 
          it now like a warmth smouldering deep within him. Fildaren began casting. 
          He silently mouthed the ancient script that was branded into his memory. 
          He had cast this spell a thousand times before and it came to him now 
          as naturally as breathing. The warmth inside him became a heat. He could 
          feel the power began to spread, rising up from deep inside him, coursing 
          out along his limbs, as tangible as anything he had ever felt. With 
          his hands Fildaren weaved the ancient magic symbols in the air that 
          would conjure the spell. A crystalline green light emanated from his 
          fingertips and he slowly wound a web of brightness about himself. He 
          felt the light settle and bind around him like a cocoon. He had cast 
          a shield spell. It was one of the first that he had ever learned and 
          it had saved his life on more than one occasion already.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">With his defences in place Fildaren turned 
          his attention to offence. He drew a small, green gem from his pouch 
          and held it in his upturned palm. Once again he cloaked himself in concentration. 
          The burning symbols of ancient runes formed within his mind’s eye, the 
          words of summoning formed upon his lips. He felt the familiar surge 
          of power as he drew upon his mana and transformed knowledge into action. 
          An emerald green circle of light formed about him, twinkling like a 
          cluster of stars in a clear night sky. The light swirled and twisted, 
          contracting upon itself until the outline of a shadowy blue figure was 
          discernible. As the malachite gem in his hand slowly dissolved into 
          nothingness the figure grew in depth and sharpness until the ethereal 
          figure of a water elemental floated a few feet above the ground in front 
          of the young mage. Fildaren sensed the mental link form between himself 
          and the elemental.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Katarnik is yours to command, Master.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">The words came to Fildaren not as sound, but 
          rather as thought. Images formed within the elf’s mind. The crisp freshness 
          of a mountain stream, the beauty of raindrops trickling amongst the 
          leaves, the crushing power of an avalanche and the irrepressible majesty 
          of an iceberg. The elemental was the embodiment of all these things 
          and it was now Fildaren’s to command. He had summoned the creature from 
          across the dimensional plane and bonded it to himself. His peers in 
          the Magicians’ Guild flippantly referred to the elementals as ‘pets’. 
          None took their pets for granted though. To each mage they were an aggressor 
          and a protector in one. They were a formidable weapon in battle and 
          a resilient shield in defence. Fildaren studied the elemental with satisfaction. 
          A translucent blue torso with thick, powerful arms, it stoically awaited 
          his command.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Hail Katarnik and well met. Time to 
          steel yourself my watery friend. We have a fine battle before us and 
          Crushbone orcs are our quarry.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;As you command, Master.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren drew his dagger from his belt and 
          clutched it tightly to him. With all his magical skills there was still 
          comfort in the feeling of cold steel in his hand. He slowly crawled 
          back up to the crest of the knoll until the orc centurions were in clear 
          view once again, the elemental drifting soundlessly behind him. He picked 
          his target, the particularly unattractive centurion standing towards 
          the front of the others, and prepared himself for battle. As his heart 
          beat faster with anticipation, Fildaren could not suppress his thoughts 
          of home. Not for the first time he considered that he might have been 
          better off staying in the corner of the Travellers Home Inn, with a 
          mug of fine ale in his hand, and a pretty eleven maiden on his arm, 
          instead of scurrying about in the cold tangling with bloodthirsty orcs. 
          He shrugged that thought off. Ideas like that did him no good now. He 
          had made his decision to lead this life and he stood by it. If nothing 
          else he could sleep at night knowing that he was making a difference. 
          No matter how small his contribution he was still taking a stand against 
          his people’s darkest foe.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">He fixed his attention upon his target once 
          more. The orc leaned against its spear, shifting its weight from one 
          leg to the next, oblivious of Fildaren’s presence.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Let the festivities begin&quot; he muttered 
          to himself as he began forming the runes of his next spell in his mind. 
          He felt the rush of power through his body as he cast an outstretched 
          hand towards his target. The unsuspecting orc suddenly burst into flame. 
          Squealing in pain and terror, the orc dropped to the ground and flailed 
          about in a crazed panic, vainly attempting to extinguish the flames 
          with its hands. Its brutish colleagues gawped in stony silence as the 
          centurion writhed in agony, seemingly too stunned to react. Fildaren 
          took full advantage of the situation and fixed his gaze upon a second 
          orc. The command passed from him to Katarnik in the twinkling of an 
          eye.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Attack!&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">With alarming speed the elemental rotated 
          in midair and sped towards the second orc, its large fists raised like 
          battering rams. The orc could not even raise its spear before Katarnik 
          slammed into it like a crashing wave, dealing it a flurry of sickening 
          blows. The orc’s knees buckled and it unceremoniously slumped to the 
          ground. The third centurion rallied in the face of this surprise attack 
          and charged towards the elemental, its short spear lowered to impale 
          the invader. Katarnik spun to face its attacker, just as the orc drove 
          its spear into the elemental’s right side. A roar of pain echoed inside 
          Fildaren’s mind, a reverberating howl of agony. The elemental slammed 
          its left fist into the head of the centurion causing it to stumble backwards 
          in a daze, leaving the spear deeply embedded in Katarnik’s torso. Then 
          the elemental raised its hands in an imitation of Fildaren’s own arcane 
          gesturing and a streaking flash of white like lightning encircled its 
          body. The light took form and hurled towards the stumbling orc, a hail 
          of razor sharp icicles tearing into the dark blue flesh of the Crushbone 
          centurion. The orc let out a bark of pain as it was slammed backwards 
          from the impact and lay twitching upon the ground, then fell deathly 
          still. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren watched in astonishment as the elemental 
          grasped the shaft of the spear in its powerful hands and, in one swift 
          movement, drew the spear from its side and cast it to the ground. Fildaren 
          gave a warm smile. The fearlessness of his elementals never ceased to 
          amaze him. He had seen them do some amazing things in his time. He still 
          sensed pain from the elemental though. The spear had pierced deeply 
          and rest was required for Katarnik to regain its strength. Two of the 
          orcs now laid prone upon the ground, one a gruesome tapestry of torn 
          flesh and inky blood and the other a charred form still consumed with 
          flickering flame. A sudden movement to the left caught Fildaren’s attention. 
          The last remaining centurion was recovering from its daze and had regained 
          its feet. He had to act quickly. Fildaren dashed towards the Crushbone 
          entrance, fighting hard to hold his concentration as he formed the runes 
          inside his mind. The orc raised its head towards the young mage, eyes 
          widening in surprise then narrowing in scornful recognition. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;High Elves! Filthy pig High Elves!&quot; 
          bellowed the orc, its face contorted in a mask of hatred and contempt. 
          ‘Guards! Guards!’ <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren’s steps faultered as three more orcs 
          emerged from the shadowy tunnel of the Crushbone entrance. The mage’s 
          heart sunk as he identified two huge legionnaires and between them, 
          the unmistakable figure of an orc oracle. Fildaren cursed under his 
          breath. He would have to plan his strategies a little better in the 
          future, if indeed he had a future. He watched helplessly as the legionnaires 
          drew their swords from their belts, their curved blades glinting menacingly 
          in the light of the bonfires. The oracle weaved symbols in the air with 
          its hands and a sickly green sphere of light enveloped it. Fildaren 
          cursed again, much louder this time. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">He gained his composure just soon enough to 
          see the centurion rushing towards him with its spear lowered in attack. 
          He felt his protective cocoon shudder as the lethal point of the spear 
          deflected against his shield spell and the weapon rattled and fell from 
          the orc’s grasp. The momentum of the centurion’s run sent him crashing 
          into the High Elf and they both crumpled to the ground with a resounding 
          thud. Fildaren grimaced as he felt the air rush from his lungs and he 
          gasped vainly for breath. Pain arched through his body from the impact 
          and his chest felt like it was going to collapse from the weight of 
          the centurion pinning him to the ground. His magical buffer protected 
          him from weapon attacks but not from the confines of gravity. The orc 
          continued its vicious attack, repeatedly slamming its broad right fist 
          into Fildaren’s jaw. The young mage’s head snapped back sharply from 
          the impact but the shield spell held, cushioning him from the pain of 
          the impact. Blow after blow weakened the shield and it was just a matter 
          of time before the spell would fail and Fildaren’s defenses would be 
          laid bare. He struggled to deny the panic that was creeping over him. 
          He was made of sterner substance than this. He would not relinquish 
          his life so easily.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Defend yourself you fool. Defend yourself.&quot; 
          The thought forged itself inside his mind as blows continued to rain 
          down upon from above. He had to repel his attacker. Through the mist 
          of his pain he identified his salvation. The feeling of cold steel in 
          his hand. Fildaren tightened his grip about the hilt of his dagger and 
          brought it up between himself and the orc. With one powerful thrust 
          he plunged the dagger into the centurion’s neck. The orc howled in agony 
          and stumbled backwards, clutching at the dagger, coal black blood gushing 
          from the wound. Fildaren rolled to his left and in one swift motion 
          had regained his feet. Wasting no time he formed the runes inside his 
          mind’s eye. He spoke the ancient commands and drew the ancient symbols 
          in the air. A crimson corona formed about him, the hazy light hardening 
          into dagger sharp points of energy that Fildaren hurled towards his 
          stricken opponent. The centurion screamed in anguish as its body was 
          torn to shreds by the magician’s attack. The orc was dead before it 
          hit the ground.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren glanced back towards the entrance. 
          Katarnik hovered between the two legionnaires, arms flailing as the 
          elemental desperately attempted to deflect the arcing blows of the orcs’ 
          scimitars. Behind the legionnaires’ merciless attack stood the oracle, 
          long fingers of light streaking out from the sphere that surrounded 
          it, each one striking Katarnik with a minute explosion of magical energy. 
          Fildaren could sense his elemental’s strength failing, its lifeforce 
          slowly fading away with each vicious blow. The young elf locked his 
          gaze towards the legionnaire closest to him. He called upon his inner 
          power, his brow furrowing with the effort to maintain his concentration. 
          One again he formed the arcane runes inside his mind’s eye, each symbol 
          a burning brand against a curtain of black. He once again conjured the 
          crimson corona around him and hurled the burning points of energy towards 
          his target. The spell struck the legionnaire with an audible blast of 
          power. The massive orc gave a mournful howl and staggered backwards, 
          fighting to keep its balance from the onslaught. Katarnik took its chance 
          and enveloped itself in a streaking blanket of pure white light. Fildaren 
          watched on as the hailstorm of ice struck the legionnaire at full force 
          and sent the orc crashing to the ground, its leather armour and skin 
          alike in tatters. Again an echo of agony reverberated inside the mage’s 
          mind. He witnessed in horror as the second legionnaire plunged its sword 
          deep into the center of the water elemental. Katarnik clutched weakly 
          at the wrist of the legionnaire, vainly attempting to draw the blade 
          out.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Forgive my failure, Master.&quot; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">The words struck Fildaren harder than any 
          blow the orcs could deal him. He watched in dismay as the figure of 
          his pet faded away to nothingness. He felt a break in the bond between 
          them, a violent snap like a rope stretched beyond its breaking point. 
          He stretched out his mind but could no longer sense the presence of 
          the elemental. A feeling of loss, of incompleteness overwhelmed him. 
          When a pet died a small part of Fildaren always died with it, so strong 
          was the bond that his magic formed between them.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Glory be to Felwithe. Glory be to the 
          Crusaders.&quot; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Anger wracked Fildaren. He roared his challenge, 
          stooped to retrieve his dagger from the centurion’s corpse, and rushed 
          towards the remaining legionnaire. He formed the arcane runes inside 
          his mind and wove the ancient symbols in the air. He looked deep inside 
          himself to draw upon his magic core and found…nothing. Fildaren stopped 
          dead in his tracks as his anger faded to alarm. His mana, the source 
          of his powers was depleted. In the heat of battle he had unwittingly 
          emptied his magical resevoir. He needed time to rest and replenish his 
          strength but time was not something he had in abundance. He cast a concerned 
          look towards the legionnaire. The mighty orc bore a mixed expression 
          of apprehension and bewilderment which was slowly turning into one of 
          cruel recogniton. The legionnaire gave Fildaren a malicious grin and 
          marched confidently towards him. The young mage froze, his feet rooted 
          in fear. The legionnaire stood head and shoulders above him and all 
          he had to defend himself was his simple blade. He considered a hasty 
          retreat but before he had a chance to act upon his decision he doubled 
          over in agony, his stomach clamped is severe cramp. His skin suddenly 
          burned with a violent fever and he broke out in a cold, clammy sweat. 
          Crouching with one knee on the ground he lifted his head back towards 
          the Crushbone entrance to see the legionnaire still striding towards 
          him and, in the background, the oracle bathed in a splotchy, insipid 
          light that stretched out its tendrils towards him. The dark arts. He 
          tried to fight the revulsion and pain that flowed through him but it 
          was too much for Fildaren to stand. The legionnaire finally reached 
          him and coiled back its powerful sword arm to strike him. The blade 
          of the scimitar came down upon Fildaren’s head with bone crushing force. 
          He felt his protective shield shudder violently and, to his growing 
          dismay, felt the spell fail as the protective cocoon around him unravelled. 
          <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;So my time has come at last&quot; regretfully 
          concluded Fildaren. He had considered that he would die this way but 
          he didn’t believe it would be so soon. He had barely begun upon his 
          path of retribution for his people and it was over before it ever really 
          began. His fate decided, there was only one thing left to do. Take this 
          bastard legionnaire down with him. From his crouched position he glanced 
          up to see the orc wind its arm back in a final deathblow. Before it 
          had the chance to complete its deed Fildaren hurled himself forward 
          and plunged his dagger into the solid left leg of the centurion. The 
          legionnaire bellowed in agony and clutched at the elven blade lodged 
          deep within its flesh. Pain coursed through Fildaren’s head as he felt 
          the orc slam the hilt of its sword against his temple. The world lurched 
          and swayed around him and he felt what strength his legs held fail. 
          He slumped to the ground and felt a dampness trickle across his eyes 
          and blur his vision. He lifted a hand to his forehead and brought it 
          back down, stained with the deep crimson of his lifeblood. Through the 
          haze he saw the legionnaire pull his dagger from its leg, leaving a 
          gaping wound behind. It cast the dagger to the ground disdainfully and 
          limped towards him, its face a hideous expression of determination. 
          A determination to see this elf dead. It stood over him for a moment, 
          relishing in the young mage’s helplessness. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren was tired. So very tired. His body 
          and soul ached but it would soon be over and sweet relief would be his. 
          He watched with a sort of emotional detachment as the legionnaire raised 
          its rusty blade above its head, taking pleasure in prolonging his agony, 
          a spiteful grin revealing the joy it took in its undertaking. He could 
          hear the mocking cackle of the oracle from somewhere in the haze beyond. 
          Fildaren looked deep into the animalistic, red eyes of the orc and waited 
          for the final blow that would end his all too short life. A blow that 
          never came. An arrow sliced through the air and slammed into the sword 
          arm of the legionnaire. As the creature squealed in surprise and agony 
          the sword rattled from its grasp. A second arrow followed and embedded 
          itself through the thick neck of the orc. In a reflex action its other 
          hand clutched at the long wooden shaft, its eyes reeling madly in an 
          attempt to identify its attacker. It had no chance. In the blink of 
          an eye a third and final arrow arched through the air and finished with 
          a loud thud in the broad chest of the Crushbone minion. The orc made 
          a gruesome gurgling noise and a steady flow of black blood gushed from 
          its mouth. It swayed unsteadily and slowly toppled to the ground with 
          a crash. The oracle was no longer laughing and with great effort Fildaren 
          tilted his gaze towards it. The orc was whipping its head from side 
          to side trying to identify the unseen assailant. The last thing Fildaren 
          saw was a bright blaze of light to his left. A luminous ball of flame 
          soared through the air and slammed into the unsuspecting oracle. He 
          watched as the dark figure was engulfed in purifying flame and tumbled 
          to the cold earth. Then all he knew was darkness.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">When Fildaren awoke he was swathed in a warm, 
          comforting blanket of healing power. He could feel the stiffness in 
          his limbs slowly fade and the dull, throbbing ache in his head lessen. 
          Energy and warmth surged through him like the feeling of an open fire 
          on a cold winter’s night. His vision cleared to be greeted by the beautiful, 
          smiling face of an Elven maid. Deep brown eyes and fine features framed 
          by chestnut hair.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Well, well.&quot; Her bell like voice 
          chimed. &quot;What do we have here? Another caster in a dress just waiting 
          to be rescued. Getting into trouble seems to be a common trait amongst 
          you High Elves. You see Cirre? He’s not dead. You owe me a gold coin.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;You’ll have to forgive Vanalin here, 
          Brother.&quot; A deeper voice replied. &quot;Wood Elves are known to 
          be a bit on the crude side but Vanalin gives the word a new meaning.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren drew himself up on his elbows and 
          took in the scene around him. The ground was littered with the corpses 
          of dead orcs and amongst the carnage stood the figures of, who he believed 
          to be, his rescuers. A petite young Wood Elf maid leaned casually upon 
          her longbow. The light of the still burning bonfires refelected brightly 
          off her ringmail armor and a quiver of arrows was slung across her back. 
          Next to her stood the more stately figure of a male High Elf. His long 
          white robe marked with the emblem of the Wizard’s guild flowed to his 
          ankles and he clutched a wooden casting staff proudly in his right hand. 
          He shared Fildaren’s features in many ways. The slim frame, fine features 
          and shock of white hair that identified male High Elves. He towered 
          over his fiesty female companion.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Ha!&quot; shot back Vanalin. &quot;If 
          I hadn’t come along you’d still be traipsing through the woods in that 
          dress of yours hoping to Tunare that you didn’t run into an orc patrol. 
          I’ve saved that pale Elven hide of yours more than once.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Cirre gave Vanalin a withering look. &quot;For 
          the hundredth time it is a robe, not a dress. Where did you learn your 
          manners? At an ogre street brawl?’ He let out a long suffering sigh. 
          &quot;Yes its true, she has assisted me on the odd occasion and she 
          refuses to let me forget it. Fair Vanalin here has the heart of a lioness, 
          fights like a she-wolf and has just about all the subtlety of a hill 
          giant.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren watched the exchange with increasing 
          amusement. The diminuitive Wood Elf stared daggers at her companion. 
          He chose this moment to intervene. He pulled himself to his feet and 
          brushed himself down. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I must disagree, Brother. She looks 
          as dainty as a butterfly and as beautiful as a rose to me.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Vanalin gave Fildaren a dazzling smile which 
          quickly turned to a scowl as Cirre snorted loudly. &quot;I think I like 
          this one, Cirre&quot; she said. &quot;We may have to add him to the 
          party to make up for your crass behaviour.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Well we can’t let you have the monopoly 
          on crass behaviour now can we, sweet lady?&quot; chuckled Cirre as he 
          cast a sickeningly sweet smile towards Vanalin.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Suddenly Fildaren felt a rush of blood to 
          his head. The ground seemed to rise up around him and he staggered forwards 
          unable to maintain his balance. He almost fell to the ground before 
          Vanalin rushed to his side and caught his arm. She gave him a sympatheitc 
          smile and assisted him down to the ground.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Careful there handsome&quot; she said. 
          &quot;I’ve cast some healing spells on you but you are a long way from 
          healthy yet. You took quite a beating there.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren slowly rubbed his temple which seem 
          to help him gain some clarity. He glanced up to see his new companions 
          watching him patiently. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;You must forgive my rudeness my friends. 
          We have not met under the most appropriate of occasions.&quot; Fildaren 
          gingerly lifted himself to his feet once again, being careful not to 
          raise himself too quickly. He stooped and swept back his hand in as 
          good an approximation of a bow as he could produce in his condition. 
          &quot;I am Fildaren, of Felwithe. Scholar of the Guild of Magicicans 
          and missionary for the Crusaders of the Soul.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">The tall High Elf returned his greeting with 
          flourishing sweep of his hand and an eloquent bow. The beautiful Wood 
          Elf gave him a delicate curtsey, never once taking her piercing gaze 
          from him. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I am Cirre, also of the great city of 
          Felwithe. Scholar of the Wizards Guild and as yet unaligned with any 
          of these new militia that seem to be sweeping our land. My hyperactive 
          companion here is Vanalin of Kelethin. A ranger from amongst the ranks 
          of Faydark’s Champions. We are at your service.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;It is I who should be at your service.&quot; 
          Replied the young mage. &quot;I take it I have you to thank for my salvation. 
          That skirmish did not go as I had planned.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;You mean you had a plan?&quot; smirked 
          Vanalin. &quot;Are all you High Elves such brilliant strategists? Rush 
          the gates of Crushbone and hope to Tunare that you don’t get your head 
          lopped off?&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Lets not be so harsh Vanalin&quot; soothed 
          Cirre. &quot;I think eagerness is our friend’s only failing here. When 
          we came upon the battle you seemed to be doing quite well with those 
          few centurions. Alas these orcs are like ants. There may be a few scuttling 
          about on top but when you kick the anthill more swarm out. Fighting 
          alone out here is a dangerous pastime my friend. You would do well to 
          align yourself with some companionship.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren nodded in agreement. &quot;Indeed. 
          I have learnt a rather painful lesson here. One I’ll not forget.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Well see that you don’t&quot; chirped 
          Vanalin. &quot;It would be a shame to lose such a fine looking elf as 
          yourself.&quot; Fildaren let out a shocked gasp as the petite Wood Elf 
          reached over and slapped him on the behind. Vanalin gave him a mischevious 
          wink and turned to go loot the orc corpses.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren turned his bewildered gaze on Cirre. 
          &quot;Watch out for that one my friend.&quot; warned the wizard. &quot;She 
          a siren. You’ll be ensnared by her song and before you know it you’ll 
          be dashed upon the rocks.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I’ll make sure to give her a wide berth&quot; 
          chuckled Fildaren. &quot;So what brings you this deep into the woods? 
          This is more than a little way off the traveled highways.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;A lot further away than I wish to be. 
          I was traveling along the Great Eastern Road towards Kelethin. I am 
          to meet some associates of mine there. The Guild of Wizards is becoming 
          increasingly concerned about the level of orc activity here in the Great 
          Forest and they had planned a meeting to discuss their role in matters. 
          I was travelling there with some of my guild brothers and sisters when 
          we were attacked by a band of forest bandits. We managed to kill a few 
          of them but the attack was swift and sudden and in the ensuing fight 
          I got separated from my party. Each tree in this forsaken place looks 
          the same to me. Luckily I crossed paths with the charming Vanalin here. 
          She can identify each tree like it is a personal friend. She is leading 
          me back to Kelethin now where I am hoping the rest of my party is waiting 
          for me. We’ve been happily disposing of a few orc patrols along the 
          way as well.&quot; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren heard Vanalin gag as she made her 
          way back down from the Crushbone entrance. &quot;Phew! Smells liked 
          fried orc up there. I don’t think I’ll be able to eat for a week. I 
          got some nice loot from them though.&quot; She jingled her purse and 
          it sung with the sweet sound of coins.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Well done.&quot; said Cirre. &quot;Single 
          handedly assisting Emperor Crush in deplenishing his wealth. A fine 
          and noble cause.&quot; All three chuckled at Cirre’s jest.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Well,&quot; concluded Vanalin &quot;if 
          that is all then I guess we should be on our way before…&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;WATCH OUT!&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Cirre barely had time to shout the warning 
          before the orc legionnaire was amongst them, its curved blade slicing 
          through the air in lethal arcs. The two High Elves dove to the ground 
          in a desperate attempt to evade its dangerous reach. The air suddenly 
          rung with the sound of steel on steel. Fildaren turned his gaze up from 
          the ground to see Vanalin, her shining blade swirling before her in 
          a flurry of strikes and parries, as she stood her ground against the 
          legionnaire. If it wasn’t for the seriousness of the situation Fildaren 
          almost could have laughed. The tiny, delicate frame of Vanalin was dwarfed 
          by the massing hulk of the legionnaire and yet it was the orc that retreated 
          as the young Wood Elf continued her assault. It was almost like a dance. 
          Vanalin swung her blade through the air with a lethal precision, balanced 
          on the balls of her feet as she turned and pirouetted. The orc legionnaire 
          madly attempted to deflect her blade with his own but the tide of battle 
          was against him. Vanalin spun and kicked the orc in the midriff causing 
          it to stagger backwards. She thrust forward with her sword and pierced 
          the orc through the left shoulder. The legionnaire let out a scream 
          of pain but managed to shove Vanalin back off balance. The ranger was 
          not discouraged and continued to push home her advantage, continuing 
          her flurry of strokes against her wounded opponent.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Get back Vanalin. Let me cast&quot; 
          shouted Cirre. Fildaren watched as the wizard surrounded himself with 
          a red corona of power.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I have it under control&quot; came the 
          irritable reply.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;You are in the line of fire. Let me 
          help.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I can handle it&quot; snapped Vanalin 
          over the clash of swords.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Vanalin’s opponent made use of her temporary 
          distraction and swung a vicious blow towards Vanalin’s neck, intent 
          on relieving her of her head. The Wood Elf deftly ducked beneath it 
          and delivered a swift kick to the right knee of the orc, sending it 
          toppling off balance. Suddenly the air was ablaze with power and Fildaren 
          watched as the red corona around Cirre compacted into a burning fireball 
          and was sent hurtling towards the unfortunate legionnaire. It impacted 
          in a fiery blaze. The orc bellowed and dropped to the ground writhing 
          in pain as Vanalin leapt forward and repeatedly drove her sword through 
          the chest of the fallen legionnaire until it struggled no longer. She 
          immediately spun on her heel and stomped angrily towards Cirre.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;You idiot! You almost killed me with 
          that fireball. Look! You burnt my hair.&quot; She brandished a singed 
          lock at the Wizard accusingly.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Well that’s gratitude for you&quot; 
          replied Cirre calmly. &quot;I save your life and all I get is abuse.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Saved my life?&quot; fumed Vanalin. 
          &quot;Saved my life!? I told you I had it under control. That orc had 
          all the fencing skills of a three legged elephant. I was about to finish 
          him off when you tried to roast the both of us.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;She’s actually madly in love with me&quot; 
          confided Cirre to Fildaren. &quot;She is just having difficulty dealing 
          with her emotions.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Madly in…I…you…&quot; stammered Vanalin, 
          her anger strangling her words. She threw up her arms with a shriek 
          of frustration and stormed off into the forest muttering about arrogant 
          High Elf wizards.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I am sorry about that&quot; apologised 
          Cirre. &quot;Sometimes I cannot resist.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;No need to apologise to me.&quot; said 
          Fildaren. &quot;I would not provoke her so openly though my friend. 
          She is an interesting mix. Both beautiful and dangerous. I would rather 
          have her fighting with me than against me.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Cirre gave Fildaren a friendly slap on the 
          back. &quot;It seems you hear that siren song already my friend.&quot; 
          Fildaren rolled his eyes and grinned in mock amusement but he secretly 
          considered that the wizard was not far from the truth.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I think the time has come to leave&quot; 
          suggested Fildaren. &quot;We risk more orcs attacking if we remain here. 
          I’ll have to return to Felwithe to report this encounter to the Crusaders 
          hierarchy.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;You should join us on our journey to 
          Kelethin. You should rest there before you take the long road back home.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Thank you for your gracious invitation. 
          I accept.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;You will have to tell me more about 
          these Crusaders along the way. I have heard a few reports about them. 
          Do you think they would accept a wizard amongst their ranks?&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;I am sure they would welcome it.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">&quot;Let us catch up with Vanalin then. She 
          is just as likely to leave us stranded here.&quot; With that Cirre dashed 
          off in the direction that the ranger had vanished.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Fildaren took a final moment to cast a glance 
          over the scene about him. The bonfires still blazed away defiantly despite 
          the fallen that scattered the ground. The standard of the Crushbone 
          orcs still whipped and fluttered in the icy breeze as a symbol of rebellion 
          against the Elven people. Fildaren realised that he had gained but a 
          small victory in a raging battle. This was an undeclared war of attrition 
          and it would only be complete when one solitary combatant was left standing. 
          He spun on his heels, turning his back on Crushbone and followed Cirre 
          into forest. Even as he walked away he felt deep within his bones that 
          he would return. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Written by Fildaren<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p><span class="whitetext9">Additional material by Vanalin<o:p></o:p></span></p>
